Headlines.Author: Steven Russolillo
Headlines.Headline: Morning MarketBeat: Housing Recovery Boosting Confidence

PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:MARKET SNAP: At 5:17 a.m. ET, S&P 500 futures flat. Treasury yields higher. Nymex down at $92.61; gold higher 0.2% at $1,768. In Europe, FTSE 100 up 0.1% , DAX down 0.3% and CAC 40 down 0.3%. In Asia, Nikkei 225 up 0.3% and Hang Seng flat.Overnight action: Delays irk American Airlines passengers; Berlin adds hitch to crisis; Diageo in talks to buy United Spirits stake.Watch for: S&P Case-Shiller home-prices index for July  (9:00 a.m. Eastern Time): prices seen rising 1%, after rising 0.5% in June. September consumer confidence (10:00): seen rising to 65.0 from 60.6 in August. July FHFA home prices index (10:00): seen rising 0.7%, same as June. Richmond Fed September manufacturing survey (10:00): came in at -9 in August.Carnival, Jabil Circuit, H.B. Fuller and FactSet are among the companies reporting quarterly results.For more MarketBeat and other streaming markets coverage from The Wall Street Journal, point your mobile browser to wsj.com/marketspulse.The Breakfast BriefingThe housing recovery could be just what consumers need to boost their confidence, and keep the stock rally going.Upbeat economic data of late have raised hopes that the worst of the housing bust is over. The positive news is expected to continue later this morning when home prices from the S&P Case-Shiller 20-city index are released.Economists anticipate prices in July rose by 1% from a year ago. An annual gain would come on the heels of the 0.5% year-over-year gain in June, which was the first time prices turned positive on an annual basis in two years.Higher housing prices, coupled with a pickup in home sales and construction activity, should have a contagious effect on consumer confidence, says Millan Mulraine of TD Securities."To the extent that homeowners get some sense of wellbeing from their perception of the performance of their home values, the turnaround in the housing sector in recent months will likely enhance their confidence," Mulraine says.The Conference Board's September consumer-confidence index is expected to jump to 65.0 after surprisingly dropping to 60.6 a month earlier, a 2012 low.Such a rebound would likely bode well for stocks, which have stalled in recent days following the big September rally. The S&P 500 has dropped in five of the last six trading sessions, although it is still up 3.6% this month and about 16% for the year.Even amid an uptick in consumer confidence, investors shouldn't expect the housing market to come roaring back to pre-crisis levels any time soon."There has been a very strong correlation between the share of distressed sales falling and the increase in home prices – which intuitively makes sense," says Tom Porcelli, chief U.S. economist at RBC.While sales of distressed homes sank to 22% last month from as high as 36% in January, more than 5 million mortgages are either delinquent or in the foreclosure process. That supply of distressed homes will continue to be detrimental to the broader housing supply,  Porcelli says."This should keep home price gains relatively muted in the medium term," he says.For now, upbeat housing data have mostly been cheered on Wall Street. The S&P home-builder index has surged 91% over the last 12 months, with D.R. PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:MARKET SNAP: At 5:17 a.m. ET, S&P 500 futures down 0.3%. Treasury yields higher. Nymex down at $91.90; gold 0.5% lower at $1,762.50. In Europe, FTSE 100 down 0.4%, DAX down 0.4% and CAC 40 down 0.8%. In Asia, Nikkei 225 down 0.5% and Hang Seng down 0.2%.Overnight action: 'Free' checking costs more than ever; Few iPhones went to retailers; Greek exit costs rise for Crédit Agricole.Watch for: Chicago Fed August national activity index (8:30 a.m. Eastern Time). Dallas Fed September manufacturing survey (10:30): came in at -1.6 in August. Lennar, Paychex and Red Hat are among companies reporting quarterly results.For more MarketBeat and other streaming markets coverage from The Wall Street Journal, point your mobile browser to wsj.com/marketspulse.The Breakfast BriefingTalk about consistency.The Dow has now gone 62 trading days without notching a single daily decline of more than 1%, according to Bespoke Investment Group. During that timeframe, the blue chip index have risen about 8%, surpassed its pre-financial crisis levels and put its all-time highs within sight.The last time the Dow dropped more than 1% was on June 25, when stocks around the world suffered a sharp selloff amid lowered expectations for any further progress on Europe's debt crisis.While such a one-sided move to the upside throughout the third quarter would seem to suggest the good times can't last forever, history says more gains could be in the offing.Since 1900, there have been 16 instances in which the Dow went an entire quarter without a one-day decline of more than 1%, while also hitting a 52-week high, according to Jason Goepfert, market-sentiment watcher at Sundial Capital Research. In each instance, the Dow was positive six months later, averaging an additional 6% gain.A flood of monetary stimulus from the Fed and other central banks around the globe have been major catalysts behind the rally, overshadowing worries about earnings, Europe and the global economy.Even though the historical data are favorable, some professionals are trying not to get greedy. As this morning's Abreast of the Market points out, several money managers are mulling whether to book profits at current levels and watch the rest of the year from the sidelines.The average, actively managed large-company stock mutual fund is up about 16% so far this year, according to Morningstar. Can't blame a manager for preserving lofty gains in the final months of the year.Still, few indicators suggest the rally is running out of steam. Even as the Dow edged down 0.1% last week, it still remains up 3.7% in September, historically the worst month of the year for stocks. The S&P 500 is up 3.8% this month and has risen 16% for the year."The S&P 500 is still technically overbought, but short-term momentum is positive," says Katie Stockton, chief market technician at MKM Partners. She predicts the market could keep coasting for the remainder of the month before hitting some trouble when October rolls around.At some point, the calm that has permeated over the market will be lifted and 1% down days will return. When that scenario plays out, chart watchers are cautioning not to overreact."When a pullback unfolds, we would not lose sight of the bullish long-term posture of the market," Stockton says.Morning MarketBeat Daily Factoid: On this day in 1968, CBS aired the first episode of "60 Minutes."-Steven RussolilloStocks to WatchHome builder Lennar is expected to report third-quarter earnings of 28 cents a share on revenue of $1.02 billion, according to a poll of analysts by FactSet.After the market closes Monday, Red Hat is seen posting second-quarter earnings of 29 cents a share on revenue of $322.1 million.Green Mountain Coffee Roasters fell another 4% Friday, following Thursday’s 10% decline, after rival Starbucks rolled out its Verismo-branded line of single-serve coffee, along with a range of electric brewers.Overnight Headlines (Links)Fed's Tarullo and Bankers Talk, Talk, TalkAhead of the Tape: The Door Is Now Open to Home BuildersAbreast of the Market: Money Managers Take a Timeout From StocksBond Investors Skeptical of New Fed PlanEuro Bulls Are Focused on SpainPlatinum Swings on StrifeAppetite for Latin Deals to Get TestCampaigns Spar Over Coal's FutureHeard on the Street: Deriving the True Size of U.S. Megabanks Is Far From Simple

Headlines.Author: Brenon Daly
Headlines.Headline: Oracle shares continue to rally

#text: Oracle

shares rallied Monday after the president of the largest database software maker told a
    European conference that it will post "flat to modest" growth in Japan for the
    current quarter. Ray Lane told the Reuters news agency that sales in Asia outside Japan
    will slide 10 percent for the quarter. At a gathering of business and political leaders in
    Davos, Switzerland, Lane also said he expected the company's core database sales to
    increase 15 to 20 percent in 1998. In the most-recent quarter, Oracle's database sales
    grew just 3 percent, sparking concern the the market for the databases, which hold vast
    amounts of information, may be saturated.
